<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="551" type="notes. hydrophorus alpinus">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">
Notes. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wahlberg" authorityYear="1844" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Hydrophorus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hydrophorus alpinus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpinus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">Hydrophorus alpinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="551">
is the commonest species on the Island, but previously only one specimen has been collected outside the warmest central part (
<bibRefCitation author="Grichanov, IYa" journalOrPublisher="Nature Conservation Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="551" pagination="23 - 31" refId="B5" refString="Grichanov, IYa, Khruleva, OA, 2018. Fauna and ecology of Dolichopodidae (Diptera) from Wrangel Island Nature Reserve (Chukotka AD, Russia). Nature Conservation Research 3 (3): 23 - 31" title="Fauna and ecology of Dolichopodidae (Diptera) from Wrangel Island Nature Reserve (Chukotka AD, Russia)." volume="3" year="2018">Grichanov and Khruleva 2018</bibRefCitation>
). In 2016 and 2019, it was discovered in six new plots (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Vyuchnyi brook. Southern gravelly slope of a hill with a &quot; tundra-steppe &quot; plant community; a site where Dolichopus terminasianae and Hydrophorus alpinus were collected. Photo by O. A. Khruleva." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/474274" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">3</figureCitation>
- 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Rogers Bay environs. Middle part of gravel-loamy foothill ridge with spotted willow-sedge-moss cover; a site where Hydrophorus alpinus was collected. Photo by O. A. Khruleva." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/474276" pageId="0" pageNumber="551">5</figureCitation>
) located mainly outside the warmest inland areas, including the coast of the Island.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
